---
import ContactCTA from '../components/ContactCTA.astro';
import Hero from '../components/Hero.astro';
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout title="About | Yuxuan Wang" description="About Yuxuan Wang — Data Scientist specializing in clinical NLP and production ML">
	<div class="stack gap-20">
		<main class="wrapper about">
			<Hero
				title="About"
				tagline="Thanks for stopping by. Read below to learn more about myself and my background."
			>
				<img
					width="940"
					height="1253"
					src="/assets/about-photo.jpg"
					alt="Yuxuan Wang at Yellowstone"
				/>
			</Hero>

			<section>
				<h2 class="section-title">Background</h2>
				<div class="content">
					<p>
						Machine learning engineer who has built <strong>production systems across healthcare, media, and finance</strong> —
						each demanding a different data intuition, a different standard for what "working" means,
						and a different relationship with the domain experts who depend on the outputs.
					</p>
					<p>
						The common thread isn't a specific technique but a disposition: building systems that
						operate reliably in production, not models that perform well in controlled conditions.
						At XpertDox, I've grown from owning clinical coding infrastructure into <strong>technical leadership</strong> —
						project management, team development, and the stakeholder work that makes delivery possible.
						At NBCUniversal, I built <strong>production forecasting</strong> across 11 digital platforms adopted
						into Finance and Ad Sales workflows. At Fosun, I tackled <strong>cold-start and cross-user variability</strong>
						in glucose prediction — not toy versions of the problem.
					</p>
					<p>
						What that range has taught me is that the hardest part of applied ML is rarely the model
						itself. It's understanding the <strong>failure modes that matter</strong> to the system, designing around
						the ones that don't, and earning the trust of the people whose workflows depend on the output.
					</p>
				</div>
			</section>
			<section>
				<h2 class="section-title">How I Work</h2>
				<div class="content">
					<p>
						The longer I work in production ML, the more my definition of a good model has shifted —
						from one with strong metrics to one that actually <strong>fits the system it lives in</strong> and
						generates measurable value there. Those aren't always the same thing.
					</p>
					<p>
						Production ownership means <strong>staying close to the outputs</strong>. I review model decisions weekly,
						interrogate production data personally to surface patterns that automated monitoring
						wouldn't catch, and turn findings into model changes within days. A model in deployment
						is a living system — monitoring is a practice, not a dashboard.
					</p>
					<p>
						In high-stakes clinical workflows, a model earns its place by serving two functions
						well: being a reliable enough <strong>confidence signal</strong> that it can eliminate review for clear
						cases, and being a sensitive enough <strong>auditor</strong> that it catches meaningful deviations from
						established rules. Getting both right requires understanding where and when the model
						<strong>should and shouldn't be trusted</strong> — which is a harder problem than building the model itself.
					</p>
				</div>
			</section>
			<section>
				<h2 class="section-title">Outside Work</h2>
				<div class="content">
					<p>
						<strong>Hip-hop</strong> has held my attention for a long time — specifically the craft of it. Writing lyrics
						forces a kind of <strong>precision</strong> that's hard to find elsewhere: a complete idea, a distinct voice,
						and something worth saying, compressed into a tight structure. What draws me most is
						hip-hop as a <strong>platform</strong> — the way it lets you say something real and get it across to people
						who might not have encountered that perspective otherwise.
					</p>
					<p>
						I watch a lot of <strong>NBA</strong> and play <strong>basketball</strong> regularly. Team sports have a particular dynamic
						I find genuinely compelling — five people with different roles working toward something
						none of them could do alone. The combination of individual excellence and collective
						coordination, and the way <strong>trust</strong> has to be built in real time under pressure, is hard to replicate.
					</p>
					<p>
						<strong>Trading card games</strong> scratch a different itch: the intersection of favorite IPs and actual
						intellectual challenge. Deck-building is a <strong>design problem with constraints</strong>, and competitive
						play is applied <strong>game theory</strong>. The fact that it wraps all of that in something you genuinely
						care about makes it easy to go deep.
					</p>
				</div>
			</section>
		</main>

		<ContactCTA />
	</div>
</BaseLayout>

<style>
	.about {
		display: flex;
		flex-direction: column;
		gap: 3.5rem;
	}

	img {
		display: block;
		align-self: center;
		margin-top: 1.5rem;
		border-radius: 1.5rem;
		box-shadow: var(--shadow-md);
		max-width: 360px;
		width: 100%;
	}

	section {
		display: flex;
		flex-direction: column;
		gap: 0.5rem;
		color: var(--gray-200);
	}

	.section-title {
		grid-column-start: 1;
		font-size: var(--text-xl);
		color: var(--gray-0);
	}

	.content {
		grid-column: 2 / 4;
	}

	.content :global(a) {
		text-decoration: 1px solid underline transparent;
		text-underline-offset: 0.25em;
		transition: text-decoration-color var(--theme-transition);
	}

	.content :global(a:hover),
	.content :global(a:focus) {
		text-decoration-color: currentColor;
	}

	@media (min-width: 50em) {
		.about {
			display: grid;
			grid-template-columns: 1fr 60% 1fr;
		}

		.about > :global(:first-child) {
			grid-column-start: 2;
		}

		section {
			display: contents;
			font-size: var(--text-lg);
		}
	}
</style>
